{Dear reader,  You are about to make your first steps in learning the Berlin
Variation against Ruy Lopez. Nowadays it's very difficult to find a top player
who doesn't play the Berlin, at least from time to time. The increasing
popularity of this opening variation is due to it's solidity and reliability. 
By emphasizing on it's solidity, I  am not saying that Black fights for a draw
in this variation. The arising positions are highly complex from a positional
point of view. In order to handle them correctly, one needs a deep
understanding and extensive amount of knowledge.   In the Berlin, it's more
important to know the basic positional concepts than memorazing concrete
variations and move orders. That's why it's almost impossible to make a
concrete preparation against a player who plays Berlin variation.   Once you
have understood the main subtleties of the arising position, you can play the
Berlin for a lifetime.  Within the framework of my current opening project, I
examine the Berlin variation in two opening databases. The first of them (
present one)is dedicated to the famous Berlin Endgame. In the second database,
I deal with all the ways in which White could deviate from this ending. 
Before we proceed with the topic, I would like to make some important
clarifications.   As I have already pointed out, in this opening, the ideas
are much more important than the choice of a concrete variation. That's the
reason why in some of the games I provide you with, Black deviates from my
suggested repertoire. Despite the different move order, the ideas remain
something stable. Moreover, since there is a variety of different move order
and possible transpositions, it's not a good idea to stick to a precise
variation. Otherwise, you couldn't make use of the main advantages of the
Berlin - it's flexibility.  Having said that, we are ready to start our
journey.  After the moves} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {We reach one of the most complicated
endgames in the chess theory - the so-called Berlin endgame. Let's try to
evaluate the situation from a positional point of view by describing the
strong and weak points of both sides:  1) Strong and weak points for White 
It's obvious that White's pawn structure is better. Black's doubled pawns on
the c-file depreciate his queenside structure, while White has an extra pawn
on the kingside. Very often, especially in the endgame, White manages to win
the game by creating a dangerous kingside passed pawn.  Also, one shouldn't
underestimate the importance of White's space advantage. The e5-pawn restricts
Black's minor pieces and at the same time makes a room for further manoeuvring.
Quite often, White generates a considerable pressure by making simple moves
like Rad1, Rfe1, Nc3-e4 and Bf4.   Despite of the abovementionned
considerations, I am convinced that White's biggest advantage is Black's
difficulty to connect his rooks. As you will see later, in a number of
positions Black solves his problems when he manages to bring his rooks into
play.   After taking into consideration White's advantages, we should point
out that Black has his own triumphs.   The bishop pair is an important asset
for him. If Black manages to open the game, his bishops could be extremely
dangerous. Despite the limited space, there are no weaknesses in Black's
position. Even his doubled pawns couldn't be considered as a weakness because
the c6-pawn controls the important squares "d5" and "b5". Please note that in
a number of endgames, White's e5-pawn could turn into weakness.  Now I would
like to bring to your attention a recent game where Anand has played the
Berlin against the strong French GM Etienne Bacrot. Even though, Anand's
choice differs from my proposed repertoire, my comments to his game will help
you to better understand the basic positional concepts in the Berlin endgame.}
9. h3 {At this point, the move order is not very important. The move 9.h3
could be played before or after Nc3 and we have a simple transposition.  
Nevertheless, we should understand the idea behind White's last move.
Generally speaking, by playing 9.h3, White is planning to gain space on the
kingside by means of g2-g4. If White manages to quickly advance his kingside
pawns, Black will find in trouble. After g2-g4, White can proceed with Ng5
followed by f4-f5.} ({Another option for White is} 9. Rd1+ {In the recent
years, the popularity of this move has increased. White's main point consists
in restricting Black's choice. Now Black king is forced to go to e8 and White
doesn't need to study the positions arising after Bd7 followed by Kc8.   On
the other hand, the move 9.Rd1 has an important disadvantage. Later, Black
will experience difficulties connected with the activation of his a1-rook. In
order to place his rooks on e1 and d1, he must waste one more tempo.} Ke8 10.
Nc3 Ne7 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge7g6,Gc8g4,Gg6e5] Remember this idea. Black wants
to generate some pressure against the e5-pawns by playing Ng6 followed by Bg4.
In general, our knight doesn't stay very well on f5. It can be easily attacked
by g2-g4 and at the same time, the mobility of black light-squared bishop is
rather restricted. That's why the manoueuvre Ne7-g6 is very desirable.} 11. Nd4
Ng6 12. Ne4 {Very important moment. By playing 12.Ne4, White is actually
preaparing f2-f4. But why he doesn't play f2-f4 immediately?} ({After} 12. f4 {
Black will accomplish an important positional idea. In Berlin, we often try to
get rid of our dark-squared bishop. This could be explained by the fact that
the activity of this bishop is highly restricted by White's e5-pawn. Generally
we prefer to exchange it for a knight ( in closed positions, knights are very
dangerous) but even the exchange of the dark squared bishops could be
advantageous for us. Later, we will discuss in detail the exchange of the
dark-squared bishops. The play may continue:} Bc5 13. Be3 Bxd4 $1 14. Rxd4 Bf5
$1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf5c2,Gh7h5,Ga8d8] This is a dream position for Black. We
could say that f5 is the perfect square for our light-squared bishop. From
here it not only attack the c2-pawn, but at the same time restrictes the
mobility of White's central pawns. It's also important to point out that
White's kingsdie pawn majority could be easily blocked by means of h7-h5.   As
the reader could see, the e3-bishop is restricted by his own pawns (it can be
restricted even more by the move b7-b6). Later on, Black will solve his
coordination problems by exchanging a pair of rooks and centralizing his king.
At the very least, we have an equal position.}) 12... h5 {As the reader
already knows, this move is always useful for us in the Berlin endgame.} 13.
Bg5 ({Suprisingly, the natural} 13. f4 {has never been played in practice.
Obviously, further tests are required. Let's take a look at one of the
possible continuations.} Bg4 14. Rd3 Rd8 15. Be3 Be7 16. h3 Bc8 17. Rad1 {Both
sides has managed to comfortably develop his pieces. I think that Black
resolved his biggest issues. His light-squared bishop operates along the
diagonal "c8-h3" without restricting the mobility of the queen's rook. Also,
the advance of White's queenside pawns is practically stopped. At this point,
I would like to point out that in this position, Black is ready to exchange a
pair of rooks. This exchange is favourable when White had already doubled his
rooks and tries to exercice pressure along the d-file.}) 13... Be7 14. Re1 h4 {
[%cal Ge7g5,Ge4g5,Gh8h5] This is another instructive moment. Very often, in
the Berlin endgame, Black tries to activate his rook by means of h5-h4
followed by Rh5. From h5, the rook attacks the e5-pawn and at the same time
controls the important f5-square. Also, given the fact that Black had gained
space by h5-h4, White couldn't start advancing his kingside pawns without
allowing a pawn exchange. According to the classical chess school, we should
always exchange pawns on the wing where our opponent has pawn majority.} 15.
Nd6+ ({After} 15. Rad1 $5 Bxg5 16. Nxg5 Rh5 17. Ndf3 Ke7 {White could hardly
improve the position of his knights. On the other hand, the e5-pawns need to
be protected in every moment. The position is approximately equal.}) 15... cxd6
16. exd6 f6 17. Bd2 Kf7 18. dxe7 Nxe7 {We have reached a complitely equal
position.}) 9... Ke8 {This is a very important decision from a positional
point of view. Black's another option is to transfer his king to the queenside.
In order to achieve it, he could have played 9...Bd7 followed by Kc8.   I
think that the move 9...Ke8 sticks better with the classical chess principles.
As a rule, our king should stay on the side where the opponent has a pawn
majority. In this way, it will be easier to fight against an eventual passed
pawn.} 10. Nc3 h5 {Despite the fact in this position, Black has a variety of
moves at his disposal, I think that the text move is his optimal choice.   By
playing h7-h5, Black fortifies the position of his f5-knight and opens the way
of his rook. Also, the move h7-h5 is designed to fight against White's
kingside expansion which could by started by g2-g4. After a possible exchange
on "g4" Black rook will actively participate in the fight.  Of course, Black's
last move has some disadvantages. Now the g5-square is weakened and White
could make use of it by playing Bg5 or Ng5. Nevertheless, I am convinced that
Black has enough resources to cover this weakness.  Other options that I
examine in detail are 11.Ne2, 11.Bg5, 11.Rd1 and 11.b3. Of course, various
transpositions are possible.} 11. Bf4 {This is the most popular continuation
for White. As I have already pointed out, White encounters problems in finding
a suitable square for his dark-squared bishop. I think that White's best
choice is to develop his bishop on "f4". After this move, the e5-pawn is
protected and the f3-knight has a room for manoeuvres. Moreover, in a number
of positions, White is ready to make use of Black's coordination problems by
opening the center with e5-e6 ( In this case, the pawn on "c7" will be hanging)
. The main drawback of the move 11.Bf4 could be explained by the fact that now
White's f-pawn is blocked and he couldn't easily execute his kingside pawn
expansion.} ({Later, in the present database, I also deal with the continuation
} 11. Ne2 {White is planning to transfer his knight to "f4" and only later he
will clarify the position of his dark-squared bishop. In a lot of positions,
the f4-knight in combination with Re1 supports the central break e5-e6.
Nevertheless, Black has enough resources to hold the equality.} Be7 12. Re1 {
[%cal Ge2f4,Ge5e6]} Be6 $1 {This is a key move! By now, the reader should have
learned that in almost every case, Black restricts the mobility of White's
central pawn by putting his bishop on e6.} 13. Nf4 Rd8 ({In my game against
Safarli, I gave preference to a different type of pawn structure:} 13... Bd5
14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. g3 c6 {We will deal with this position later. For now, I
would say that it's approximately equal.}) 14. Nxe6 fxe6 {This position was
reached in the game Volokitin,A-Rabiega,R played in 2011. Here, the pawn
structure is very typical for the Berlin endgame and it's very important to
learn it in depth.   Generally speaking, I consider the exchange on e6 as
favorable for Black. Now we can make use of the f-file to bring our h8-rook
into play. Also, I would say that our e6-pawn is extremely powerful. It
strengthens the position of the f5-knight and at the same time takes the
control of the important d5-square. That's why Black can gain additional space
by playing c6-c5 without weakening the d5-square (due to the weakness of d5,
we generally avoid playing c6-c5. This principle is especially valid in
positions where White has a chance to bring one of his knights to d5 and then
play c2-c4.).   Nevertheless, you should be aware of some positional traps.
First of all, it's necessary to avoid entering a knight endgame. As the knight
endings are very close to the pawn endgames, White wins rather easily. It is
impossible to prevent our opponent from creating a kingside passed pawn
because white knight manages to fight against every kingside pawn
configuration. It goes without saying that the pawn ending is lost for Black.
In this case, there are some study like exceptions but they are something very
rare.   Generally the endings with dark-squared bishops are favorable for
White but Black could hold them. Remember that in such case, it's necessary to
have pawns on h5, g6 and e6 ( the king stays on f7). White is going to put his
king on e4 and then he will start to prepare the advance f4-f5 by means of
g2-g4. After exchanging the g and h pawns, Black should stay without touching
his e6-pawn. According to the endgame theory, this endgame is completely
holdable though some precision is still required.   As for the rook endgame,
it's an easy draw because after the massive pawn exchanges, Black manages to
generate a counterplay along the open files.   If Black manages to exchange
his dark-squared bishop for a knight, he is clearly better because in the
arising ending, his knight dominates the opponent's dark-squared bishop.})
11... Be7 {This is by far the most popular move. Nevertheless, my
recommendation is based on the somewhat more flexible 11...Be6. My idea could
be explained by the fact that depending on the circumstances, Black's
dark-squared bishop could be developed either via b4 or via e7 while his
light-squared bishop always goes to e6. That's why it makes sense to first
start with the mvoe 11...Be6. Later, this line will be examined in depth.} 12.
Rad1 Be6 13. Ng5 Rh6 {This rook lift is quite a typical idea. Black rook not
only takes the control over the important e6-square but at the same time we
are ready to bother White king by means of Rg6.} ({Black shouldn't remove his
bishop from "e6". For example, after} 13... Bc4 {White can start gradually
preparing the move e7-e6.} 14. Rfe1 Rd8 15. b3 Bd5 {And now White obtains a
clear advantage by means of} 16. e6 $1 Bxe6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Bxc7 {Black has
an exposed king and his pawn structure is spoiled.}) 14. g3 {An important
positional move which is designed to prevent Black from fixing White's
kingside pawns by means of h5-h4.} ({Despite the fact that the move} 14. Nxe6 {
is rarely seen in practice, it has a solid positional background. White
eliminates opponent's bishop pair and prepares a kingside pawn expanision.  
Let's follow the game Hovhannisyan - Bacrot played in 2012 in Plovdiv.} Rxe6
15. g4 hxg4 16. hxg4 Nh4 17. Ne2 f5 $1 {An instructive positional idea. As we
have pointed out, it's advantageous to exchange pawns on the wing where our
opponent has a pawn majority. Moreover, after the elimination of the e5-pawn,
White's spatial advantage will disappear.} 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. Ng3 {Now follows
are a forced sequence leading to a draw.} Bxb2 20. Rb1 Bd4 $1 21. Rxb7 Bb6 22.
Bxc7 Re7 23. Rb8+ Rxb8 24. Bxb8 Nf3+ 25. Kg2 Ne1+ 26. Kh3 g6 {[%csl Rh3][%cal
Ge7h7]} 27. g5 Nf3 28. Bf4 Rh7+ 29. Kg2 Nh4+ 30. Kg1 Nf3+ 31. Kg2 Nh4+ 32. Kg1
Nf3+ 33. Kg2 {Draw by repetition. We can draw the conclusion that the move 15.
g4 leads to a draw almost by force.}) 14... Bxg5 15. Bxg5 Rg6 16. h4 {[%csl
Rg6][%cal Gc3e2,Ge2f4] White is planning to make use of the restricted postion
of the g6-rook by the manoeuvre Ne2-f4.} ({To a draw by repetition leads the
continuation} 16. Bf4 {For instance:} Nh4 17. Kh2 Nf3+ 18. Kg2 Nh4+ $11) 16...
f6 {This only move seems to be more than enough. Black's counterplay is based
on the vulnerable h4-pawn.} 17. exf6 gxf6 18. Bf4 Nxh4 19. f3 {[%cal Gg1f2,
Gf1h1] White takes away the f3-square from the knight and at the same time
wants to proceed with Kf2 followed by Rh1 attacking the h5-pawn. Despite of
being pawn down, currently, he has the initiative.} Rd8 {It's always good to
exchange a pair of rooks when your opponent has the initiative.} 20. Rde1 Kf7
21. Kf2 Nf5 22. Rh1 Ng7 {A typical move for the variation. Now the h5-pawn is
safely defended.} 23. Ne4 ({After} 23. Rd1 {I think that Black should play} Rc8
{Even though Black's last move looks slighlty passive, it's important to
defend the c7-pawn because it controls the critical d6-square.}) ({White
couldn't achieve his goals by taking the pawn immediately as Black manages to
neutralize the threats by exchanging a pair of rooks. For example:} 23. Bxc7
Rd2+ 24. Re2 Rxe2+ 25. Nxe2 Rg5 {Here, the h5-pawn is defended by the rook and
black knight is ready to cover the d6-square. The positions is already equal.})
23... Rc8 $1 {Anand correctly estimates the importance of his c7-pawn.} 24. Nc5
Bf5 25. c4 {This move is slightly imprecise.} ({White should have tried to
pose some practical problems by} 25. b3 $1 {threatening to take the b7-pawn as
Rb8 followed by Rxb2 is no longer possible. Now Black could reach the equality
in two different ways:} b6 26. Na6 Ne6 (26... c5 27. Nxc7 Bxc2 28. Re2 Bf5 29.
Nb5 Ra8 $11) 27. Rxh5 Ng7 28. Rh2 Ne6 $11) 25... b6 26. Ne4 Re8 27. Bxc7 Bxe4
28. Rxe4 Rxe4 29. fxe4 Ne6 {Black has managed to solve all the problems. Now,
by a temporary sacrifice of two pawns. he will activate his rook.} 30. Bb8 Rg8
31. Bxa7 Ra8 32. Bxb6 Rxa2 33. Be3 Rxb2+ 34. Kf3 Rb3 35. Kf2 Rb2+ 36. Kf3 Rb3
37. Kf2 Rb2+ {And the draw was agreed.} 1/2-1/2

