1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 10. h3 h5 11. Bf4 Be6 {This is my favourite weapon
against the main line. As I have pointed out in the introduction, this
approach is much more flexible. Depending on White's next move, we will decide
where to place our dark-squared bishop. Generally speaking, the bishop should
be developed on "b4" when White plays Rad1 + Rfe1. In this way, due to the pin
along the a5-e1 diagonal, White can prevent the exchage Bxc3 (the reader
already knows that in the Berlin endgame, Black tries to get rid of his
dark-squared bishop).  On the other hand, if White opts for Rfd1, then Black
should develop his bishop on "e7" since the move Bb4 is well met by Ne4.} 12.
Rad1 {Even though this move is quite natural, I think that White should
prevent his opponent from playing Bb4. Despite the fact that the optimal
set-up is Rad1 + Rfe1, it's more important to restrict the exchanges which are
favorable for the opponent.} ({The logic behind the abovementioned
consideration is confirmed by the fact that even an expert like Gata Kamsky
gives preference to the move 12.Rfd1. His game against Navara played in 2012
is particularly important.} 12. Rfd1 Be7 ({Now the move} 12... Bb4 {is well
met by} 13. Ne4) 13. Ng5 Rh6 $1 {Again, Black makes use of this key idea. This
is the only way in which he can bring his kingside rook into play.} 14. Nxe6
Rxe6 15. Kf1 {So far, Navara was playing in a flawless manner. In this
important position, I provide you with a stron novelty which puts into doubt
White's entire concept.} g5 $146 {Now white dark-squared bishop is forced to
occupy a passive position. Later on, the e5-pawn will be attacked. First of
all, however, it's recommendable to neutralize White's initiative by
exchanging a pair of rooks.} 16. Bh2 Rd8 17. Rxd8+ Kxd8 18. Rd1+ Kc8 19. Ne4
Nh4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh4g6,Gg6e5] Black is ready to attack the central pawn by
means of Ng6. Now it's White who should care about the equality.}) ({After} 12.
Ng5 Rh6 13. Nxe6 Rxe6 {We reach a position which is similar to the game Kamsky
- Navara.}) 12... Bb4 13. Bd2 ({Now} 13. Ne4 $2 {loses an exchange after} Bc4 {
[%csl Gb4,Gc4,Re1,Rf1][%cal Gb4e1]}) 13... Rd8 $1 $146 {Before exchanging his
dark-squared bishop, Black wants to take the control over the open file. It's
interesting to mention that this natural move was a novelty at the time when I
have played it.} 14. Bg5 Rd7 $1 {This move is quite typical for the Berlin
endgame. Black is already planning to transfer his king to the queenside in a
suitable moment. In this way, he not only brings the kingside rook into play,
but at the same time black king supports an eventuall pawn expansion on the
queenside.} 15. Rxd7 ({It seems that White could put 12...Bb4 into question by
playing} 15. Ne4 $5 {but Black manages to immediately challenge white knight's
central position.} Bd5 {Black pieces are perfectly coordinated and White has
no chance to fight for an advantage.}) 15... Kxd7 16. Rd1+ Kc8 17. a3 $2 {
After this careless move, White spoils his queenside pawn structure. As an
addition to his better pawn structure, Black achieves an endgame with opposite
coloured bishops which is always good for Black in the Berlin variation.} ({In
order to prevent Black from spoiling his queenside structure, White should
have played the passive} 17. Ne2 {Even in this case, however, Black overtakes
the initiative by playing} Bd5 $15 {[%csl Re2,Re5,Rf3][%cal Gh8e8] followed by
Re8. The e5-pawn is rather weak while and White has difficulties with the
stability of his knights. Black's advantage is obvious.}) 17... Bxc3 18. bxc3
c5 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Rc2,Rc3,Gc6][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gb7c6,Gc6b5,Gb5c4,Gb5a4,Ga4a3,
Gc4c3] Black is playing according to the classical positional rules. In
positions with opposite coloured bishops, we should place our pawns on the
colouf of our opponent's bishop. Now white g5-bishop is restricted by Black's
queenside pawns. Moreover, I am planning to activate my king c6-square. Later
on, the king could eventually attack White's weaknesses by Kb5-c4 (a4).} 19.
Nh4 $1 {White makes a good positional decision. With a knight on f3, he can't
move forward his kingside pawns. Next few moves are quite logical.} Nxh4 20.
Bxh4 b6 21. f4 Bf5 22. Rd2 Kb7 23. Kf2 Kc6 {[%cal Gc6b5,Gb5c4]} 24. c4 $1 {
This is White's best chance. In order to play Kb5, Black should eliminate the
c4-pawn with his bishop. Meanwhile, White is going to start pushing his
kingside pawn majority.} Be6 25. Ke3 Bxc4 26. f5 b5 27. c3 a5 28. Rd8 $1 {
Vuckovic continues to resist in the best possible way. Black was planning to
create a queenside passed pawn and to place his rook behind it. In that case,
white rook would have been very passive. That's why White correctly decided to
exchange the rooks.} Rxd8 29. Bxd8 Kd7 30. Bg5 Bf1 {Black commits an
inaccuracy. Even though he is still winning, the move 30...Bf1 is a step in
the wrong direction.} ({Better was} 30... a4 {[%cal Gb5b4] planning b5-b4. The
game may continue} 31. e6+ fxe6 32. f6 gxf6 33. Bxf6 Kd6 34. g4 hxg4 35. hxg4
Ba2 {[%cal Ga2b1] With an easy win. White's g-pawn could be easily stopped by
Bb1. Later on, Black will create a new passed pawn by playing b5-b4.}) 31. Kf2
Bc4 32. Ke3 b4 33. cxb4 cxb4 34. axb4 axb4 35. Kd4 Bf1 36. h4 Bxg2 $2 {After
this mistake, the position is draw.} ({Of course, Black is still winning. He
should have played} 36... Kc6 {Here are some variations:} 37. g3 (37. e6 f6 38.
Bd2 b3 39. Kc3 Bxg2 40. Kxb3 Bh3 41. e7 Kd7 42. Bf4 c6 43. Bd6 Bxf5 44. Kc4 g5
$19) (37. Bd8 Bxg2 38. Kc4 Bh3 $19) 37... Kb5 38. Be7 Bh3 39. f6 g6 $19) 37.
Kc4 c5 38. Kxc5 b3 39. Bc1 g5 40. fxg6 fxg6 41. Kc4 Ke6 42. Kxb3 Kxe5 1/2-1/2

