{Now I want to show you a game which illustrates what could happen if White
starts a premature advance of his kingside pawns.   My opponent is GM Arkadij
Naiditsch who is reknown for his theoretical knowledge and ambitious play.
However, if you are too ambitious against the Berlin, you could get an
inferior position out of the opening. That's why I play this opening at any
level. Weaker players dont understand very well the positional background of
the variation, while top players tend to be too ambitious from time to time. 
In my game against Naiditsch, after the moves} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 {My
opponent decided to save a tempo on 10.h3. He played directly} 10. Bf4 Be6 11.
g4 $6 {This kingside activity is premature. Of course, White could proceed
with 11.h3 and after the obvious 11...h5, the game will transpose into our
main line. Now Black's counterplay is based mainly on the unprotected
positions of f4-bishop and g4-pawn.} ({White doesnt manage to generate
pressure after} 11. Ng5 Bc4 12. Rfd1 h6 13. Nge4 Rd8 $11 {Black's position is
entirely safe while White has run out of constructive ideas.}) 11... Ne7 12. h3
Nd5 {During the game, I was convinced that Black should centralize his knight
before proceeding with h7-h5.} ({However, such a considerations is far from
obvious. Sometimes, the move h7-h5 could be very well combined with the idea
Ng6. Let's take a look at the following variation:} 12... h5 {[%csl Rg4,Rh3]
[%cal Gh5g4,Ge6h3]} 13. Nd4 {This knight jump is the only way to defend the
kingside pawns.} Bc4 14. Rfd1 (14. Rfe1 hxg4 15. hxg4 Nd5 {Black has overtaken
the initiative since his pieces are very active while white king is somewhat
exposed.}) 14... Ng6 15. Bg3 Bb4 {We have reached an approximately equal
position. Black has managed to solve his opening problems. With a pair of
bishops in an open position, he can face the future with confidence.}) 13. Bd2
h5 {Probably, it was better to immediately exchange the knights in order to
free d5-square for the bishop. Nevertheless, during the game, I wanted to
generate pressure against opponent's kingside by keeping my bishop on the
c8-h3 - diagonal.} ({After} 13... Nxc3 14. Bxc3 h5 15. Ng5 Bd5 $15 {Black's
advatage is obvious.}) 14. Nd4 Bd7 {As I was focused on the idea to keep the
bishop on the diagonal c8-h3, I have missed an interesting sequence which
allows me to grab the initiative.} ({After} 14... Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bc4 16. Rfe1
hxg4 17. hxg4 {Black has at his disposal the energetic} c5 18. Nf5 Bd5 19. f4
Rh3 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gg7g6,Gf8e7,Gd8h8] White king is very weak. Black could
follow with 0-0-0, g7-g6, Be7 and Rdh8. In some cases, c5-c4 followed by Bc5
is also possible.}) 15. f3 Bc5 16. Nce2 hxg4 17. hxg4 f6 $1 {This typical idea
was already discussed. By exchanging the e5-pawn, Black eliminates White's
spatial advantage and opens up the position for his pair of bishops.} 18. exf6
Nxf6 19. c4 Kf7 {Black has established a perfect coordination between his
pieces. In this open position, the bishop pair is a valuable asset. Moreover,
Black is better developed and his rooks are ready to occupy the open files.  
Later, I have commited some inaccuracies and the game ended in a draw. I leave
the rest of the game without comments as it's nothing to do with the typical
Berlin ideas.} 20. Kg2 Bd6 21. Rh1 c5 22. Nf5 Bxf5 23. gxf5 Rhe8 24. Rae1 Rad8
25. Bg5 Be5 26. Ng3 b6 27. b3 Bc3 28. Rxe8 Rxe8 29. Bf4 Be5 30. Bxe5 Rxe5 31.
Kf2 Re8 32. Rd1 Rh8 33. Ke3 a5 34. Ne4 Ke7 35. Rg1 Ne8 36. Rg2 Rh1 37. Kf4 a4
38. Re2 Kd7 39. Rd2+ Ke7 40. Re2 Kf8 41. Ng5 Rd1 42. bxa4 Rc1 43. Ne6+ Kf7 44.
Ng5+ Kf8 45. Ne6+ Kf7 46. Ng5+ 1/2-1/2

