1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. h3 Ke8 10. Nc3 h5 11. Ne2 {The idea behind this move was
explained in depth in my comments to the introduction game Bacrot - Anand.
Nevertheless, it's useful to recall some of the basic points.  By playing 11.
Ne2, White is planing to transfer his knight to the active f4-square, thus
supporting the key e5-e6 advance. For the moment, he does not make clear his
intentions concerning the development of the dark-squared bishop.   As the
reader already knows, Black could counter the idea Nf4 + Re1 followed by e5-e6
by putting his bishop on e6. In the introduction, I explained why Black
shouldn't fear the structure arising after an exchange on e6. We just need to
know which pieces to keep on the board.} Be7 $1 {It's important to start with
this move. Black is planning to meet 12.Nf4 with g7-g5 followed by g5-g4. So,
if White is really trying to realize the e5-e6 advance, he should start with
12.Re1 and play Nf4 only in case of Be6.} 12. Re1 {This is the main though not
the only move. Let's take a look at the alternatives.} ({Quite a tricky
positional move is} 12. Bg5 {Now, White is going to meet the natural} Be6 {with
} 13. Nf4 {White's main positional idea consists in executing the following
exchanges: Nxe6 and Bxe7. Later on, after an eventual exchange of the rooks
along the d-file, White will enter a knight endgame which is highly favourable
for him as we already pointed out in the introduction. However, Black is not
forced to enter this endgame.   After} Bd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {We reach a pawn
structure which will be examined later in my comments to the current game.}) ({
White could prevent the opponent from transferring his bishop to d5 by playing
} 12. Rd1 {Now} Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] is met by} 13. Nf4 {Despite the fact that
White has managed to stop the ideas connected with Bd5, his set-up has some
disadvantages. As I have pointed out, one of the main ideas behind the
manoeuvre Ne2-f4 is to support the e5-e6 advance. With a rook on d1 instead of
e1, this idea doesn't work so well. Now Black could simply play} Bc8 $1 {[%cal
Gg7g5,Gg5g4] Threatening g5 followed by g4. If the rook was on e1, the move 13.
..Bc8 would have been met by 14.e6! It seems that White's best is to accept
the repetition arising after} 14. Ne2 Be6 15. Nf4 Bc8 $11) 12... Be6 13. Nf4
Bd5 {This is a key idea for this line.} ({If you prefer to enter the structure
arising after Nxe6, I advise you to go for} 13... Rd8 {Note that the exchange
on e6 is highly advantageous for Black in positions where they control the
open d-file. As we already know, the e6-pawn increases the control over the
important d5-square and stabilizes the f5-knight. Furthermore, White has
problems to create a kingside passed pawn.} 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bf4 c5 {[%cal
Ge8d7,Gd7c6] Black's last goal consists in establishing a line of
communication between his rooks. In order to achieve it, he can activate his
king by Kd7-c6.} {If white tries to prevent this idea by means of} 16. Ng5 {
Black enters his desired type of ending - strong knight against a bad bishop.
Moreover, after transfering his king to c6, he has a free hand to gain space
on the queenside. White has run out of counterplay.} ({White's typical idea to
enter a knight ending by} 16. Bg5 {doesn't work in view of} Nd4 $1 {[%csl Rf3,
Rg5][%cal Gd4f3,Ge7g5]} 17. Nxd4 cxd4 {[%cal Gd8d5] Black is already slightly
better since it's easier for him to create a passed pawn.}) 16... Bxg5 $1 17.
Bxg5 Rd5 18. Rad1 Kd7 19. f3 Kc6 20. Kf2 h4 {With an excellent play for Black.}
) 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {We have reached a fundamental pawn structure which should be
known by every Berlin player.   In this position, White's main positional
asset is his e5-pawn which not only gives him a considerable spatial advantage
but at the same time restricts the mobility of Black's pieces. Moreover, there
is no connection between Black's rooks since his king is stuck in the centre.
We should also take into consideration the fact that black knight lacks
stability on f5.   On the other hand, Black managed to fix his pawn structure
and now he should find a way to connect his rooks, eliminate opponent's
spatial advantage and find a better position for his knight.    Black has two
main plans at his disposal. If he focuses on the elimination of opponent's
spatial advantage, he shoud give preference to f7-f6 followed by Kf7. Even
though, this plan may be enough for equality, Black continues to experience
problems with the somewhat ackward position of the f5-knight.   I think that
first of all, Black should activate his knight and deal with the dangerous
e5-pawn. This could be achieved by means of g7-g6 followed by the typical
manoeuvre Ng7-e6. In this way, it's almost impossible for White to achieve
something on the kingside. Note that the f3-knight prevent White from gaining
additional space on the kingside by means of f2-f4. When the e5-pawn is safely
blocked, white e1-rook also loses his potential too.   Later on, Black could
connect his rooks by means of the manoeuvre Kf8-g7 ( sometimes it's even
possible to transfer our king to the queenside ).   White's only constructive
idea is to make use of the fact that Black's plan is time-consuming. For
example, he could try to open up the position with some kind of a pawn break.}
15. g3 {This move prevents Black from playing the typical h5-h4.} c6 16. Rd1
Rd8 {With this natural move Black strengthens his centre and is now ready to
proceed with his plan.} ({Nevertheless, if we look at the position a little
bit deeper, we will give preference to the move} 16... a5 {Besides gaining
space on the queenside, there is another important idea behind this move. This
idea will become clear a little bit later.}) 17. Bf4 g6 18. a4 Ng7 19. Be3 a6
20. b4 $3 {I have complitely missed this move. White sacrifices a pawn in
order to invade opponent's camp via b7. Such a rook could be extremely
dangerous when our king is still in the center. That's why Black should have
played 16...a5.} Ne6 {Black proceeds with the execution of his main idea. This
approach, however, seems to be too slow.} ({Nevertheless, I should have
accepted the sacrificed pawn. Let's take a look at the following forced
variation:} 20... Bxb4 21. Rab1 a5 22. c3 Bxc3 23. Rxb7 Ne6 24. Rc1 d4 25. Bd2
Rd7 26. Rb8+ Rd8 27. Rxd8+ Kxd8 28. Bxc3 dxc3 29. Rxc3 Kc7 30. Nd2 Rb8 31. Nc4
Rb4 32. Nxa5 c5 33. Nc4 Rxa4 {The draw is the most probable outcome.}) 21. b5
Kd7 $6 ({The attempt to spoil White's pawn structure by} 21... h4 $5 {is very
well met by} 22. Kg2 {Here, after} hxg3 23. fxg3 axb5 24. axb5 cxb5 25. Ra7 Rc8
26. Rxb7 b4 27. Rd2 {White keeps an advantage due the misplaced h8-rook.}) 22.
Bb6 ({A logical continuation would have been} 22. c4 {White continues to open
up files against the black king. The game may continue} Kc8 23. Bb6 Rd7 24.
cxd5 Rxd5 25. Rxd5 cxd5 26. Rc1+ Kd7 27. Rd1 axb5 28. axb5 Ra8 29. Rxd5+ Ke8 {
White is pawn up and his advantage is undisputable. On the other hand, Black
keeps drawing chances due to the fact that he managed to activate his pieces.})
22... Ra8 23. bxc6+ Kxc6 24. a5 Rhc8 25. Rab1 Kd7 $1 {Black's only chance
consists in sacrificing the central pawn. Otherwise, White will follow up with
the manoeuvre Rb3-c3 and the game will be over.} 26. Rxd5+ Ke8 27. Nd4 $2 {A
strange decision by my opponent. Black wants to exchange the b6-bishop for his
knight anyway. After such an exchange, the a5-pawn will become quite
vulnerable.} ({White should have preferred} 27. Be3 Nd8 28. Rb2 Rc3 29. Kf1
Rac8 30. Ne1 {With a slight advantage.}) 27... Nc7 28. Bxc7 Rxc7 29. Kf1 $14 {
Probably, White is still somewhat better here. However, after exchanging the
rooks by means of 29...Rd8 30.Rxd8 Bxd8, Black is ready to attack
simultaneously a5 and e5 pawns. That's why my opponent offered a draw which
was accepted.} 1/2-1/2

