1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 10. b3 {White tries to deviate from the main moves 10.
h3 and 10.Rd1 but this plan is not ambitous at all. In the Berlin endgame, b2
is not a very comfortable square for the bishop. White dark-squares bishop is
restricted by his central e5-pawn and contrary to the lines where the bishop
is on f4, here, the advance e5-e6 is not a threat ( c7-pawn is not hanging ).}
Ne7 {Even though Black has a variety of good options, I like this flexible
approach. After playing 10...Ne7, Black could start bothering the f3-knight by
means of Bg4. Depending on the concrete circumstances, the e7-knight could go
to g6 or d5. Sometimes even Nf5 works well ( as in the current game ).} 11. Bb2
{The most natural but probably not the best move.} ({Given the fact that by
playing 10...Ne7, Black has lost his control over the central d4-square, White
should have tried to centralize his knight.} 11. Nd4 $5 {Now Black must reckon
not only with the central break e5-e6 but also with an eventual pawn expansion
on the kingside. For example, under favorable circumstances, White could go
for f4-f5. Despite the obvious advantages of the move 11.Nd4, this knight
lacks stability. Black manages to make use of this factor in a very
instructive way.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd1,Rd4][%cal Gg4d1,Ga8d8,Gd8d4] Black last
move is designed to prepare 12...Rd8. As the bishop controls d1-square, white
knight couldn't be protected by means of Rd1.} 12. f3 Rd8 $1 {This
intermediate move is the point of Black's previous play.} 13. Rd1 Bc8 {Black
has managed to develop his queenside in an optimal way. Now, depending on
White's next move, he will decide how to deploy his kingside pieces.} 14. Bg5 (
{A mistake is} 14. Bb2 {as Black could challenge the d4-knight by playing} Nf5
{Here, it becomes obvious that the move 12.f3 is highly favorable for Black.
Moves like Bc5 and Ne3 are already in the air.  After} 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 {[%csl
Rc2][%cal Gf5c2] The c2-pawn is quite problematic.}) 14... h6 15. Bh4 {Now
Black could execute a typical idea which allows him to generate a considerable
pressure against e5-pawn.} g5 {[%csl Re5,Gg5][%cal Gf8g7,Ge7g6,Gg7e5,Gg6e5,
Gg5f4] Black is planning to attack the e5-pawn by means of Bg7 followed by Ng6.
Due to fact that he has a pawn on g5, White couldn't protect his central pawn
by playing f3-f4. This approach is very sound in positions where White can't
make use of the weakened f6-square. This is obviously the case here.} 16. Ne4 {
[%cal Ge4f6]} Bg7 17. Bg3 Ng6 18. Rd2 $1 {[%cal Ga1e1] This is quite a tricky
idea. White keeps the control over the d-file and at the same time he intends
to question the position of his opponent's king by playing Re1.} ({The move} 
18. Nf6+ {helps Black to centralize his king. Note that white knight is quite
vulnerable on f6.} Ke7 19. c3 h5 20. h3 h4 21. Bh2 Nxe5 22. Bxe5 Bxf6 23. Bxc7
Rd5 {Black's pawn structure is fixed and he has an advantage due to the pair
of bishops.}) 18... Nxe5 19. Re1 Ke7 20. Nxg5 hxg5 21. Bxe5 Bxe5 22. Rxe5+ Kf6
23. Ree2 {We have reached a roughly equal position. The activity of Black's
pieces compensates his slightly damaged pawn structure.}) 11... Bg4 12. Nd4 {
It's understandable that White doesn't accept positions with a spoiled pawn
structure.} ({Worse is} 12. Rad1 {For example:} Ng6 13. Rfe1 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Bb4
$1 {Now Black will manage to exchange his most passive piece. In the arising
endgame, black knight dominates the bishop.} 15. Re4 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Ke7 {
Black's advantage is out of question. After exchanging a pair of rooks along
the d-file, he can establish a solid blockade on e6 and f5 squares.}) 12... Rd8
13. Ne4 Nf5 {As the reader should have seen by now, the strange looking
combination Bg4 + Nf5 works very well. After the exchange of the knights,
Black has a tremendous activity.} 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. Rfe1 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg2g4,
Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} h5 $1 {This is a real profilactic move. By gaining space on the
kingside, Black stops all the ideas connected with h3 followed by g4.} 16. c4
$6 {A careless move which not only the d-file but also the second rank. Now
Black has the chance to invade opponent's camp.} ({More stubborn was} 16. h3 {
After} h4 17. Re3 Rh6 18. Rae1 Bb4 {Black has an edge but there are is a lot
of fight.}) 16... Bb4 17. Re3 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 Rd2 19. Bd4 Ke7 $15 {Black
centralizes his king and prepares to bring the h8-rook into play. White
doesn't have a comfortable way to deal with the upcoming threats.} 20. Be3 Rc2
21. e6 {In order to generate some kind of counterplay, White is forced to go
for his pawn sacrifice. Otherwise, Black will develop his initiative by
playing Ke6 followed by Rd8.} fxe6 22. a3 Bd6 23. b4 b6 24. Re1 c5 $1 {Fixes
the c4-weakness and restricts the mobility of the e3-bishop.} 25. bxc5 bxc5 26.
h4 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b2] Of course, black rook occupies the open file. Now the
move Rbb2 is in the air.} 27. Bf4 Kd7 $1 28. g4 (28. Bxd6 {doesn't help either.
For instance:} cxd6 29. Rxe6 Rxc4 30. Re7+ Kc6 31. Rxg7 Rxh4 32. Rxa7 Rd4 {
Black is winning.}) 28... g6 $1 29. gxh5 gxh5 30. R1e3 Rf8 (30... Rb1+ 31. Kg2
Rbc1 $17) 31. Rd3 Rf5 32. Be3 a6 33. Kf1 Ke7 34. Ke1 Kf7 35. Kd1 Rb2 36. Kc1
Re2 $19 0-1

