{This game features the move 11.Rd1. Even though this move became quite
popular recently, I am convinced that with a precise play Black manages to get
a comfortable equality.   In the present game, I focus on the positional ideas
for both sides while in my comments to the game Kamsky - Ragger, I deal with a
variety of concrete variations.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5.
d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 10. h3 h5 11. Rd1 {I
think that this move is not so useful in positions where Black had already
played Ke8. As I have already pointed out, in Berlin, White plays Rd1 in order
to prevent Black from transfering his king to the queenside. As it's obviously
not the case here, 11.Rd1 doesn't make so much sense. White usually connects
this move with the idea to double his rooks along the d-file, after playing
Bg5.} Be7 12. Bg5 Be6 {Black has managed to develop his minor pieces. Now, in
case of necessity, he could exchange a pair of rooks by means of Rd8. On the
other hand, the kingside rook could be activated via h5 after the typical
h5-h4 advance. That's the idea White wants to prevent with his next move.} 13.
g3 Rg8 $1 {This move shows Black's deep understanding on the position. Black
is planning to play f7-f6 and after a possible pawn exchange, his rook will be
very active on the g-file.  This position is very important because it arises
also via different move order - 11.Bg5 Be6 12.Rfd1 Be7 13.g3.} 14. Kh2 $1 {
This is a good prophylactic move. White not only improve the position of his
king but at the same time he leaves the dangerous opposition along the g-file.}
f6 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Bf4 Nd6 {We have reached a pawn typical Berlin pawn
structure.  At first sight, it looks that White retains some edge due to the
Black's spoiled pawn structure. Nevertheless, a deeper look at the position
will convince us that things are far from simple. The position was opened up
and Black's pair of bishop is potentially dangerous. Moreover, I would like to
point out that black pawns are not weak at all. The doubled pawns on "c7" and
"c6" cover the important central squares "d6" and "d5" while the e5-square is
protected by black f6-pawn. That's why white knights lack stability since
there are no outposts for them.   Not that Black can already establish a
coordination between his rooks by means of Kf7 (this idea is possible thanks
the the f6-pawn). The position is approximately equal.} 17. Nd4 ({If White
wants to restrict the mobility of black minor pieces by means of Ne2 followed
by b2-b3 and c2-c4, then Black could make use of temporary weakened e4-square.
For instance:} 17. Ne2 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc2c4]} Kf7 18. b3 Rae8 19. c4 Ne4 {With
an excellent play for Black.}) 17... Bd7 18. Rd3 ({After} 18. Re1 Kf7 19. Ne4
b6 20. Rad1 Rad8 {Black is perfectly OK. A possible plan for him is to play
c6-c5 and Bc6 followed by doubling the rooks along the d-file. In such kind of
positions, the bishop pair starts to tell.}) 18... Kf7 19. Re1 Rge8 20. Rdd1
Bf8 21. Bc1 $2 {It's difficult to understand the idea behind such a move.
Instand of the bishop retreat, White should have played f2-f3 followed by
g3-g4 thus restricting the activite of black light-squared bishop.} Rad8 22.
Rxe8 Rxe8 23. Kg2 c5 24. Nde2 Bf5 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf5c2] Black's advantage is
undisputable. In such kind of positions, it's very difficult to protect the
weak c2-pawn. Of course, White's main problem is to find a suitable squares
for his knights.} 25. Rd5 $4 {This is a blunder.} Rxe2 0-1

