{In the game Tarlev, K - Lysyj, I , we have explained why it's good to play
Rg8 in case of Bg5. Since the reader is already familiar with the basic ideas,
we are ready to deal with some concrete variations.   Lets take a look a model
game played by GM Gata Kamsky who is a big expert in this variation. It's
interesting to mention that he normally uses a tricky move order we should be
familiar with.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6
dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Rd1+ {Kamsky is already trying to prevent
the opponent from transferring his king to the queenside.} Ke8 10. h3 {A very
subtle move order. In the introduction to the Berlin endgame, we have seen
that Black meets the move 10.Nc3 by means of Ne7 followed by Ng6 and
eventually Bg4.  After 10.h3, however, the knight manoeuvre doesn't work in
the best way. For example, if Black plays 10...Ne7, White could respond with
11.Bf4. Now the move 11...Ng6 could be met by 12.Bh2. Note that in this move
order White's positions is very flexible since his queenside knight could be
developed even via d2. That's why in some cases the manoeuvre Nd2-c4 is
possible.  After taking into account the abovementioned considerations, I
recommend the move} Be7 {Now our normal position is reached after the moves}
11. Nc3 h5 12. g3 Be6 13. Bg5 Rg8 14. Kh2 ({Instead of 14.Kh2, White could try
to generate some pressure along the central files. For example, it's
interesting to examine the move} 14. Rd2 {Of course, after playing 13...Rg8,
Black is forced to go for} f6 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Bf4 {It turns our that in this
concrete position, the move 16...Nd6 is already not in Black's favor since
White has the possibility to double his rooks on the "e" file. The following
line is highly instructive.} {After 16.Bf4, Black should play} Rc8 {As we have
already pointed out, it's very important to defend the c7-pawn because after
taking it, White could make use of the weakened d6-square. Now we are ready to
play Kf7 establishing a coordination between the rooks. Black's problems are
over.} (16... Nd6 17. Re1 Bxh3 18. Bxd6 cxd6 19. Rde2 ({In case of} 19. Rxd6 {
Black could react with} Kf7) 19... Rg7 20. Nh4 Rc8 ({similar to the main line
is} 20... Rb8 21. Kh2 Bd7 22. Ng6 Rxg6 23. Rxe7+ Kd8 24. Rh7) 21. Kh2 Bd7 22.
Ng6 Rxg6 23. Rxe7+ Kd8 24. Rh7 {White's advantage is obvious. He threatens not
only to win back the pawn but also to invade opponent's 7th rank. Black is
doomed to passivity.})) 14... f6 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Bf4 Rc8 {As we have seen in
the game Tarlev - Lysyj, 16...Nd6 is enough for an equality. I would say that
Ragger's approach to the position is somewhat more ambitious. With his last
move Black prefer not to close the way of his dark-squared bishop by the
passive knight retreat. His next move could be Kf7.} 17. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Ge2d4]
Since White knights have no outposts, Kamsky is trying to exchange at least a
pair of knights. His next move will be 18.Ned4.} Nd6 {Now this move is forced.
In this position, you should avoid exchanges of the minor pieces because in
the endgame, White is better due to Black's spoiled pawn structure.} 18. Ned4
$1 Bd7 19. Nh4 {This move is designed to fight for the important f5-square.
This is a classical prophylactic approach. In general, by making a
prophylactic move, we not only prevent our opponent from realising his ideas
but at the same time we improve our position. That's why the prophylactic move
is not a defensive one. Here, White is playing against Black's idea to play 19.
..Kf4 and at the same time, he improves the position of his knights.} Rd8 $1 {
Black's last move illustrates his huge understanding on the position. It turns
out that black d7-bishop should be protected. Otherwise, White will proceed
with 20.Bxd6 followed by 21.Ndf5.} ({After} 19... Kf7 {White could go for the
following instructive variation:} 20. Bxd6 Bxd6 21. Ndf5 $1 {This is the
problem. Since the d7-bishop is not protected Black is now forced to part with
one of his bishops.} Bxf5 22. Nxf5 {I consider these exchanges as being
favorable for White. He has an advantage in every endgame, since his pawn
structure is better.}) 20. Rd3 Kf7 21. Rad1 Rge8 22. b3 ({Now the idea} 22.
Bxd6 Bxd6 23. Ndf5 {doesn't work very well for White since Black has already
occupied the e-file. For example:} Bxf5 24. Nxf5 Re5 $1 {This precise move is
a computer suggestion.} ({I am almost sure that Kamsky rejected this variation
due to the rook invasion:} 24... Re2 {Nevertheless, here, White has an
interesting ideat at his disposal} 25. Nd4 ({The move} 25. R1d2 {loses on the
spot because of the simple trick} Rxd2 26. Rxd2 Bxg3+ {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gd8d2]})
25... Rxf2+ 26. Kg1 {[%csl Rf2] Suddenly, it turns out that black rook is
trapped. Even here, however, Black has enough resources to generate
counterplay.} Bxg3 $1 27. Rxg3 Rxc2 $1 {With a huge compensation for the piece.
}) 25. Nxd6+ {White is forced to go for this unfavorable exchange since any
knight retreat allows Re2 or h4 with a strong initiative for Black.} (25. Ne3
h4 $1 {[%csl Rg3,Rh2][%cal Gd6h2] Black gets rid of his weak h-pawn and at the
same time spoils White's kingside pawn structure.}) ({The same idea work after
25.Nd4 either.} 25. Nd4 h4) ({In case of} 25. Nh4 $2 {Black wins material after
} Re2 {[%csl Rc2,Rf2][%cal Ge2f2,Ge2c2] White can't protect his pawns. As we
know,} 26. R3d2 $2 {is impossible because of} Rxd2 27. Rxd2 Bxg3+ $18 {[%csl
Rd2][%cal Gd8d2]}) 25... cxd6 26. Rxd6 Rxd6 27. Rxd6 Re2 {WIth equality.})
22... c5 $1 23. Ne2 Bc8 {This move is somewhat passive.} ({Generally, in the
Berlin endgame, after playing c6-c5 we should try to cover the weakend
d5-square as soon as possible. That's why Black should have preferred the
active} 23... Bc6 $1 {[%cal Gc5c4] White not only activates his bishop but at
the same time he is planning to get rid of the doubled pawns by means of c5-c4.
White must react.} 24. c4 Ne4 $1 {Another important positional subtlety. In
positions where your opponent has doubled his rooks along the d-file, you
should eliminate his initiative by exchanging a pair of rooks. Please not that
you should keep at least one rook, otherwise, it's difficult to create
conterplay.} 25. Rxd8 Bxd8 26. f3 Ng5 27. Ng1 a5 {Black has a comfortable
equality.}) 24. c4 Ne4 25. Be3 Rxd3 26. Rxd3 Bd6 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] After
covering all the weaknesses, Black has obtained a better position. After 27...
b6 followed by Bb7, he want's to establish a perfect coordination between his
pieces while white king starts feeling some danger.} 27. Kg2 {[%csl Rf5][%cal
Gf2f3,Gg3g4,Ge2g3,Gh4f5,Gg3f5] Good positional move. White wants to restore
his control over the f5-squre. This could be done by means of moves like f2-f3,
g3-g4 followed by Ng3.} b6 {This move is quite natural but Black should have
tried to prevent White from executing his plan.} ({The coordination between
white pieces could have been spoiled by means of} 27... Ng5 {[%csl Rh3][%cal
Gg5h3,Gc8h3] And only when White protects his h3-pawn by playing} 28. Ng1 {
Black could follow up with his standard plan} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] With an
advantage.}) 28. f3 Ng5 29. g4 $1 {After taking back the control over the
f5-square, White gradually manages to equalize.} Bb7 30. Ng3 hxg4 31. hxg4 Bc6
{[%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6d7] Black must take the d7-square under control since
Whtie is going to attack black dark-squared bishop by means of Ngf5.} 32. Ngf5
Bf8 $6 {This move seems to be too passive. Now White can activate his king via
g3.} ({The natural} 32... Be5 {was to be preferred.} 33. Bf2 Ne6 $11 {with
equality.}) 33. Kg3 $14 Ne6 34. Bh6 Be7 35. Nxe7 $3 {Excellent positional
decision! Indeed, at first sight, the f5-knight is stronger than black
dark-squared bishop. Nevertheless, now White could bring his h4-knight into
play via f5. At the same time, without his dark-squared bishop, Black has
problems to defend his queenside pawns.} Rxe7 36. Nf5 Rd7 37. Rxd7+ Bxd7 38.
Bf4 a5 39. Ne3 a4 40. Nd5 axb3 41. axb3 Bc6 42. Be3 Bb7 {Black continues to
play passively.} ({The variation} 42... Bxd5 43. cxd5 Ng7 {leads to a simple
draw. Actually, the text move doesn't lose either but some precision is still
required from Black.}) 43. Kf2 b5 44. Ke2 bxc4 45. bxc4 Bc6 $2 {After this
move, Black's position is already hopeless.} ({Black could achieve an easy
draw by means of} 45... Nd4+ $1 46. Bxd4 ({The move} 46. Kd3 {doesn't change
anything.} Nxf3 47. Nxc7 Ne5+ 48. Kc3 Nxg4 $11) 46... cxd4 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 47.
Nxc7 d3+ 48. Kxd3 Bxf3 49. c5 Bxg4 {The draw is obvious.}) 46. f4 $1 {White is
already winning. Kamsky demonstrates a perfect endgame technique until the end.
} f5 $2 {This is Black's last mistake after which White wins quite easily. The
rest of the game is left without comments.} ({Black could have prolonged the
resistance by playing} 46... Ba4 {The game may continue} 47. Nc3 Bb3 48. Kd3
Nd8 49. Bxc5 Nc6 50. Nd5 {Gradually, White is going to convert his advantage.})
47. gxf5 Bxd5 48. cxd5 Ng7 49. Bxc5 Nxf5 50. Kd3 Kf6 (50... Ke8 51. Ke4 Nh6 52.
Ke5 $18) 51. Bb4 Kf7 52. Ba5 Ne7 53. Kc4 Ke8 54. Bxc7 Kd7 55. Bb6 Ng6 56. Be3
Ne7 57. Kc5 Nf5 58. Bc1 Kc7 59. Kc4 Kd7 60. Bd2 Kc7 61. Ba5+ Kd7 62. Bb6 Ng3
63. Kd4 Nf5+ 64. Ke5 Nh6 65. Bc5 Ng4+ 66. Kf5 Nh2 67. Kg6 Nf3 68. f5 Ne5+ 69.
Kg7 Nd3 70. f6 1-0

