{This game features White's attempt to develop his dark-squared bishop on g5.
As I have pointed out on a number of occasions, White encounters considerable
problems in finding a good square for his dark-squared bishop.   I think that
the way in which Ni Hua deals with the g5-bishop is quite instructive. The
reader will not have difficulties in understanding Black's moves because the
vast majority of the ideas are already familiar to us.  Let's take a look at
the game.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7.
dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 10. h3 h5 11. Bg5 {This move is mainly
desinged to restrict the mobility of black pieces. As the reader already knows,
in the Berlin endgame, the move Bg5 is usually connected with an eventual
doubling of the rooks along the open d-file. As a rule, if Black manages to
neutralize white's immediate threats, he obtains a reliable position. One of
the main drawbacks of the move 11.Bg5 is that in a variety of positions, Black
could play the typical f7-f6 with a tempo.} Be6 12. Rfd1 Be7 13. b3 {White
keeps applying his restriction strategy. Generally speaking, in the Berlin
endgame, the move b2-b3 is played with the idea to restrict black
light-squared bishop. Later on White could proceed with Ne2 or Ne4 followed by
c2-c4. If Black allows this scenario, he will be doomed to passivity until the
end of the game.} f6 {Again, this typical idea seems to be Black's best
options. In general, this is the best way to fight against opponent's spatial
advantage. Furthermore, Black intends to connect his rooks by means of Kf7.}
14. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gh2c7] As always, after f7-f6, the h2-b8 diagonal
will be opened and White decides to target the important c7-pawn.} Rc8 15. Ne2
{[%cal Ge2d4] With his last move White wants to challenge the stability of
Black's e6-bishop by playing Ned4. However, Black has enough resources to keep
the balance.} ({Nothing changes after} 15. Ne4 {[%cal Gc2c4] planning c2-c4.
The play may continue} Kf7 16. c4 b6 17. Rd2 h4 {With an equality.}) 15... Kf7
16. Ned4 ({After} 16. exf6 gxf6 17. c4 Bc5 18. Rd3 Rhe8 19. Ned4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4
Bd7 $11 {The pair of bishops gives Black a comfortable equality.}) 16... Nxd4
17. Nxd4 g5 $1 {I have already mentioned this idea in my comments to the game
Kamsky - Navara. Black not only gains space on the kingside but at the same
time his play is directed against white dark-squared bishop. His next move
will be f5.} 18. Be3 f5 19. f4 g4 20. hxg4 hxg4 21. Nxe6 Kxe6 {Black has a
comfortable equality since white central passed pawn is safely blockaded.} 22.
Kf2 Rh2 23. Rh1 Rch8 24. Rxh2 Rxh2 {Black's pieces are much more active but
the game is draw as no break is possible.} 25. Rd1 a5 26. a4 Rh8 27. c4 b5 28.
cxb5 cxb5 29. Rc1 bxa4 30. bxa4 Rb8 31. Rxc7 Rb2+ 32. Kg3 Rb3 33. Kf2 Rb2+ 34.
Kg3 Bb4 35. Rc1 Kd5 36. Rd1+ Ke6 37. Rc1 Kd5 38. Rd1+ Ke6 1/2-1/2

