{Despite the fact that the following game doesn't follow our main line, I find
it extremely instructive for everyone who want's to master the typical ideas
in the Berlin. We should also take into considration the fact that this is a
top player's game ( Caruana - Andreikin ) in which two big experts in the
Berlin endgame face each other.   First 13 moves are already known for us from
the game Bacrot - Anand.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6
6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. h3 Ke8 10. Nc3 h5 11. Bf4 Be7 12.
Rad1 Be6 13. Ng5 Rh6 {In this position, White deviates from the main move 14.
g3. Instead, he prefers to bring his f1-rook into play as soon as possible.}
14. Rfe1 {Now White hopes to generate a considerable central pressure.
Nevertheless, the reader already knows that the construction Rd1 + Re1 has an
important drawback. Black could get rid of his passive dark-squared bishop by
creating a pin along the a5-e1 diagonal. Andreikin immediately seizes that
opportunity.} Bb4 {It's interesting to see that this is a sound idea even in
positions with a tempo down. This could be explained by the fact that in
closed positions, the static positional factors are often more important than
the wasted time. Even though this consideration is often valid for the Berlin
endgame I prefer to advoid wasting time. That's why I have came to the
conclusion that 11...Be6 followed by Bb4 eventually is a more sound and
flexible approach.} 15. Nge4 $5 $146 {Caruana introduces a new idea. By
choosing a positional approach, he refrains from the most popular 15.g4. White
not only centralizes his knight, but at the same time, he prevents his oponent
from spoiling white queenside pawnstructure by means of Bxc3. Later on, he
intents to start advancing his kingside pawn majority.} ({We must say that
after 15.g4, White's results are far from spectacular. As an example, I
provide you with a small part of the game Radjabov - Andreikin played in 2014.
} 15. g4 hxg4 16. hxg4 Ne7 17. Nxe6 Rxe6 18. Kg2 {[%cal Gf4g3,Gf2f4,Gf4f5] We
have reached a typical situation. White gradually prepares his kingside pawn
expansion. Later on he is planning to proceed with Bg3 followed by f2-f4-f5.
In order to equalize, Black should follow three easy steps.  1) exchange his
dark-squared bishop by Bxc3  2) neutralize White's initiative by exchanging a
pair of rooks  3) stop the advance of White's kingside pawns.  In the game,
Andreikin manages to execute this plan in a flawless manner.} Bxc3 19. bxc3 Rd8
20. Rxd8+ Kxd8 21. Rh1 {Now it's easy to stop White's kingside play. This
could be achieved by the typical Nd5 followed by g5.} Nd5 22. Bg3 g5 {Black
has managed to solve all the problems. In this concrete position, his knight
is stronger that teh g3-bishop. At the same time, White should pay attention
to his queenside weaknesses. The position is rather balanced.}) 15... Rg6 16.
Kh2 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf2f3,Gg3g4] White's idea is to follow with g2-g3, f2-f3 and
g3-g4. If he manages to achieve it, Black will find himself in a big trouble.
That's why he should react.} h4 17. g4 {Nevertheless! White wants to gain
space on the kingside and to restrict the mobility of the g6-rook. The
drawback of this idea is that now white central e5-pawn will be considerably
weakened.} hxg3+ 18. fxg3 Ne7 {This is a typical idea in the Berlin endgame.
Since, on f5, black knight lacks good perspectives, Andreikin wants to
redirect it to d5. In this way, Black manages to change some pieces, thus
making opponent's spatial advantage insignificant.} 19. a3 Bxc3 {Black finally
goes for this favorable exchange.} 20. Nxc3 Nd5 {Black continues to apply his
strategy. After an eventual exchnage of the knight, the position will be
completely equal.} 21. Ne2 $1 {Of course! When you have a spatial advantage,
you should avoid piece exchanges} ({The position arising after} 21. Nxd5 cxd5
22. b4 c6 23. g4 Kd7 $11 {Is complitely equal.}) 21... Ke7 22. g4 Rh8 23. Kg2
Nxf4+ 24. Nxf4 Rgh6 25. Nxe6 $6 {I think that this exchange is a little bit
premature. White knight could create some new weaknesses by attacking black
pawns from different squares. Maybe, White should have played 25.Re3. Even
after this move, however, the position remains approximately equal.} Kxe6 {Now
king is optimally placed and White should take care of his weak e5-pawn.} 26.
Rd3 a5 27. a4 b6 28. Re4 Re8 29. Red4 c5 30. Rf4 Rhh8 31. Kg3 Rd8 32. Rdf3 Rhf8
33. g5 {[%cal Gg5g6] White's last chance is to execute the g5-g6 break.
Andreikin deals with White's ideas in the best possible way.} Rd1 $1 {In the
endgame, there are is nothing more important than the activity of our pieces.
Now 34.g6 will be met by 34...Rg1.} 34. h4 Re1 {Now the weak e5-pawn starts to
tell.} 35. Rf5 g6 ({The move} 35... Rxe5 {seems to be too risky. After} 36.
Rxe5+ Kxe5 37. h5 {White manages to create an outside passed pawn.}) 36. Rf6+
Ke7 37. Rc6 Rc8 38. Kf4 Kd7 39. Rf6 Ke7 40. b3 Rh8 41. Kg3 Rh7 42. Rc6 Kd7 43.
Rcf6 Ke7 44. Rc6 Kd7 1/2-1/2

