{In my comments to the game Bacrot - Anand, I emphasised on the fact that
Black should always be happy to play an endgame in which his knight fights
against opponents dark-squared bishop. In his game against Gashimov played in
2011, Ruslan Ponomariov shows how to play for a win in such endgames. His
remarkable technique is highly instructive for everyone who wants to have a
deep understanding on the Berlin subtleties.  After the moves} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.
Rd1+ Ke8 10. Nc3 Ne7 11. Nd4 {Ponomariov went for the rare} Bd7 {With his last
move Black prepares Ng6 which is often followed by Rd8. Black dark-squared
bishop is usually developed on "e7". In a long-term, Black intends to give a
fight for the open d-file.  Despite the fact that Ponomariov deviates from my
proposed repertoire (as you can see in my comments to the game Bacrot - Anand,
I advocate the move 11...Ng6 here), this game should be studied due to the
important endgame concepts.} 12. Ne4 {This is probably the best continuation.
White has centralized knights and now he wants to develop a strong initiative
by means of Be3 followed by f2-f4.} Ng6 13. f4 Be7 14. Re1 {This is a little
inaccuracy. I think that White should finish the development and double his
rooks along the d-file without wasting time.} ({The game Idani - Lami, 2014 saw
} 14. Be3 Rd8 15. a4 a5 16. h3 h5 17. Rd2 {[%cal Ga1d1]} Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5]
This is a typical manoeuvre for the Berlin endgame. Black wants to exchange a
pair of knights by playing 18...Nf5. Generally, Black always tries to achieve
an endgame where his pair of bishops is fighting against bishop and knight. In
order to make use of his spatial advantage, White shouldn't allow this
exchange. That's why he played} 18. Ng3 g6 $1 {Black insists on his idea.} 19.
Rad1 Nf5 20. Ngxf5 gxf5 {It looks like black pawn structure is even more
spoiled now, but in fact, now White couldn't make use of his kingside pawn
majority. Black has covered all the weaknesses in his camp.} 21. c4 c5 22. Nb5
Bxb5 23. Rxd8+ Bxd8 24. axb5 b6 {with a complitely equal position.}) 14... c5
$1 {This is a key move. By restricting the mobility of white d4-knight, Black
is planning to place his bishop on the perfect e6-square. As I have already
mentioned, this move is advantageous in positions where White couldn't play
Nd5 followed by c2-c4.} 15. Nf3 Be6 16. Nfg5 {This move is clearly in Black's
favor. In general, Black is happy to exchange his dark-squared bishop for a
knight. Such an exchange is extremely favorable in positions where White's
kingside play is stopped by h7-h5 and Black controls the d-file.} ({Better was
to keep the tension by} 16. Be3 b6 17. Rad1 {When Black should go for} Rd8 $1 {
The exchange of a pair of rooks is favorable for Black. Since White enjoys a
considerable spatial advantage, Black wants to reduce the material. Otherwise,
White was going to double his rooks along the d-file and organize an annoying
pressure against black king.} 18. Rxd8+ Bxd8 19. b3 Kd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] This is
a known idea in Berlin. By transferring his king to c6, Black brings his rook
into play and solves his opening problems. The position is equal.}) 16... Bxg5
{This is one of the most typical Berlin ideas. After exchanging his
dark-squared bishop for a knight, Black builds a light square strategy.
Generally, the construction Bf5 + h5 is a rock-solid. White dark-squared
bishop is restricted by his own pawns. It's already a little bit easier to
play with Black.} 17. Nxg5 Bf5 {From f5, the bishop not only controls
important light squares on the kingside, but at the same time he attacks the
c2-pawn. If this pawn goes forward, the d3-square will be seriously weakened.}
18. Ne4 b6 19. Ng3 $1 {Very instructive moment. White sacrifices his c2-pawn
in order to activate his dark-squared bishop by means of f4-f5. Of course,
such a pawn shouldn't be accepted!} Ne7 $1 {This is a wonderful positional
decision. Black knight is ready to occupy the important f5-square. Everyone
knows, that when we want to make a blockade, we need a knight.} 20. Nxf5 Nxf5
21. c3 {White is forced to accept this positional concession. Otherwise, the
threat of Nd4 is quite annoying.} h5 {[%csl Rd3,Gf5,Gh5] Black has a dream
position. White kingside pawn majority is complitely blocked while Black can
make use of the weakened d-square. The manoeuvre Rd8 - d3 followed by c5-c4 is
always in the air. Another important idea for Black is to eliminate White's
spatial advantage by playing Ke7 followed by f7-f6.} 22. Kf2 Rd8 23. Be3 Ke7
24. Rad1 f6 25. exf6+ Kxf6 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. Bc1 a5 $1 {In positions where
your opponent has no counterplay, you shouldn't be in a hurry. It's always
useful to strengthen our position before taking concrete actions. White is
doomed to passivity. His bishop couldn't enter the game since he is restricted
by the f4-pawn. Moreover, Black is ready to proceed with the typical c4
followed by Rd3.} 28. a4 c4 29. g3 Rd3 {Black has achieved everything he could
hope for in the Berlin variation. In the following sequence, Ponomariov
doesn't rush at all. He is looking for the optimal set-up of his pieces. White
could hold the position since he doesn't have obvious weaknesses. Nevertheless,
in positions without counterplay, it's easy to commit a mistake.} 30. Ke2 Ke6
31. Bd2 Rd5 32. Rf1 g6 33. Rf3 Kf7 34. Rf1 Rd8 35. Bc1 Ke6 36. Re1 Rd3 37. Bd2
Rd8 38. Kd1+ Kf7 39. Re5 Nh6 40. Kc2 Ng4 41. Re2 Nf6 42. Be1 Rd6 43. h3 (43.
Bf2 $1) 43... Rd3 44. b3 Rf3 45. bxc4 h4 46. gxh4 Rxf4 47. c5 $2 {So far,
White defended very well. His last move, however, is an obvious mistake.} ({
The draw could have been achieved by} 47. Kd3 {After} Nd7 48. Bf2 c6 {I
propose the following pawn sacrifice:} 49. c5 $3 bxc5 50. Bg3 Rxa4 51. Bd6 {
Black's counterplay is enough for a draw.}) 47... Rxa4 48. cxb6 cxb6 49. Re5
Re4 $19 {Black finally finds out the right plan. After exchanging the rooks,
he can make use of his outside passed pawn on the queenside. After a long
fight, Black managed to convert his advantage.} 0-1

